    "rationale": "This reaction is a classic example of the Houben-Hoesch synthesis, where an electron-rich arene (1,3,5-trimethoxybenzene) is acylated by a nitrile (acetonitrile) using a Lewis acid catalyst (zinc chloride) and a mineral acid (HCl). The reaction proceeds via electrophilic aromatic substitution to form an aryl ketone. This specific example is frequently cited in textbooks and illustrates the key transformation of the reaction family with simple, acyclic, and RDKit-parseable structures.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The Houben-Hoesch reaction is a specific type of electrophilic aromatic substitution (acylation) using a nitrile and a Lewis acid. This example uses a simple, highly activated arene (phloroglucinol trimethyl ether) and a simple nitrile (acetonitrile) to avoid overlap with more general Friedel-Crafts acylations (which typically use acyl halides or anhydrides) or the Gattermann reaction (which uses HCN or its derivatives to form an aldehyde). The chosen substrates are simple and lack complex functionalities that could trigger other named reaction classifiers."
  }
